04740nam a22007095i 9780823296491DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20211994nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232964917 a10.1515/97808232964912doi  a(DE-B1597)575315  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0150002bisacsh1 aDeMolen, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReligious Orders of the Catholic Reformation /cRichard DeMolen. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (290 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPublished in honor of John C. Olin, Professor Emeritus of History at Fordham University, for his many contributions to the study of Catholic reform in the sixteenth century, this is an assembly of nine essays on Catholic religious orders of that period. The contributors devote attention to the spirituality of the founder(s) and to the specific apostolate of the order. The focus of the essays is on the religious communities that were founded between 1524, when the Theatines arose, and 1621, when the Piarists were recognized by the papacy as a religious order. Most of these orders were founded for reasons unrelated to the crisis posed by Protestantism, but they were soon enlisted by the hierarchy to counteract its effects. If the Council of Trent (1545-1563) can be considered the architect of Catholic reform and renewal, and the papacy and episcopate as its enforcer, surely the religious orders of men and women in the sixteenth and early seventeenth centuries ought to be considered as the initiators or disseminators of reform while serving as missionaries, teachers, preachers, catechists, and confessors. The contributors are: Kenneth J. Jorgensen, S.J., Albertus Magnus College; Elisabeth G. Gleason, University of San Francisco; Richard L. DeMolen, Erasmus of Rotterdam Society; Charmarie J. Blaisdell, Northeastern University; John W. O'Malley, S.J., Weston School of Theology; Jodi Bilinkoff, University of North Carolina-Greensboro; John Patrick Donnelly, S.J., Marquette University; Wendy M. Wright, Creighton University; Paul F. Grendler, University of Toronto.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh1 aBilinkoff, Jodi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlaisdell, Charmarie J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeMolen, Richard L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonnelly, John Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGleason, Elisabeth G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrendler, Paul F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJorgensen, Kenneth J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Malley, John W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWines, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWright, Wendy M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311074329640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329649140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823296491423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823296491/original  a978-3-11-074329-6  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA